{
  "texts": [
    "To conclude, using only one feature's category when predicting student's academic performance has shown its popularity, even though the significance of using more than one category of features cannot be ignored, as many studies have proven that the use of two or three categories of features leads to the discovery of greater student's patterns.",
    "For the studies that have only used one category of feature, as shown in Figure 17, the majority (about 69%) have selected student activity features, followed by student current academic features (about 26%), while only Xiong et al (2022) utilized student demographic features for predicting student's academic performance.",
    "The studies that have combined two categories of features for prediction as shown in Figure 18, have observed that the use of student demographic features in many studies (42%) is combined with either student current academic (39%) or activity features (19%) to help develop more accurate models of student's academic performance and identify students who are at risk of failure.",
    "Moreover, it has been noted that none of the studies that have used one or two categories of features utilize student's previous academic features, either because previous academic features may not be available, may not be relevant, or may not be predictive for the chosen task.",
    "For the studies that have used three categories of features, as shown in Figure 19, (about 33%) of the studies used student demographic features combined with student current academic features (30%) and either student activity features (27%) or student's previous academic features (10%)."
  ]
}